g.text: History
JavaScript was initially created to make web pages alive.
When JavaScript was created, it initially had another name: LiveScript. But Java
was very popular at that time, so it was decided that positioning a new language
as a younger brother of Java would help.
The programs in this language are called scripts. They can be written right in a
web pages HTML and run automatically as the page loads.
Scripts are provided and executed as plain text. They dont need special
preparation or compilation to run.
Initially, we used JavaScript only to build apps that run inside our browsers.
Every browser has a JavaScript engine that takes our JavaScript code and
converts it to code that computers understand.
In 2009, Ryan Dahl came up with a brilliant idea. He took Googles V8 engine
and embedded it in a C++ program and called that Node.
Today, JavaScript can execute not only in the browser, but also on the server, or
actually on any device that has a special program called the JavaScript engine.
Examples of JavaScript Engines
- Internet Explorer - Chakra - Mozilla Firefox - Spidermonky
- Google Chrome - V8 - Safari - WebKit

g.text: Specs, Manuals and Compatibility
ECMAScript is specification. JavaScript is a programming language that confronts
this specification.
The ECMA-262 specification contains the most in-depth, detailed and formalized
information about JavaScript. It defines the language.
A new specification version is released every year.
MDN (Mozilla) JavaScript Reference is the main manual with examples and other
information.
Its great to get in-depth information about individual language functions,
methods etc.
JavaScript is a developing language, new features get added regularly.
To see their support among browser-based and other engines, see:
- caniuse
- kangax compat table
You can find it at developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference
The latest specification draft is at tc39.es/ecma262.

g.text: Tips for Comments
An important sign of a good developer is comments: their presence and even
their absence.
Good comments allow us to maintain the code well, come back to it after a delay
and use it more effectively.

Avoid this:
- Overall architecture, high-level view.
- Function usage
- That tell how code works and what it does.

descriptive that it doesnt require them
- Important solutions, especially when not immediately obvious.

g.text: Data Types
There are 8 basic data types in JavaScript.
And one non-primitive data type:
object for more complex data structures.
Seven primitive data types:
- number for numbers of any kind: integer or floating-point
- bigint for integer numbers of arbitrary length.
- string for strings. A string may have zero or more characters, theres no
separate single-character type.
- boolean for true/false.
- null for unknown values a standalone type that has a single value null.
- undefined for unassigned values a standalone type that has a single
value undefined.
- symbol for unique identifiers.

g.text: Identifiers
All Variables must be identified with Unique Names. These Unique Names are
called Identifiers.
Rules for Identifiers:
- cannot be a reserved keyword
- should be meaningful
- Identifier must start with character or $ or _ only.
- may have digits but can't start with digits
- can't have special characters except dollar($) or underscore(_).
- are case-sensitive

g.text: String Comparison
There are only 6 values that are considered falsy in JavaScript:
- The keyword false
- A number or BigInt representing 0 (0, 0.0, 0n)
- The empty string ('', "")
- The primitive value null
- The primitive value undefined
- The global property NaN
Every other value is considered truthy. It's important to remember that this
applies to all JavaScript values, even ones that might seem falsy, such as empty
arrays ([]) or empty objects ({}).
